Go ahead.

00:32:00.710 --> 00:32:01.616
AUDIENCE: Can you
talk a little bit

00:32:01.616 --> 00:32:02.975
about the film "The Worthy"?

00:32:02.975 --> 00:32:04.790
Because it's also
quite [? different. ?]

00:32:04.790 --> 00:32:05.781
ALI MOSTAFA: Ah, yes.

00:32:05.781 --> 00:32:06.280
OK.

00:32:06.280 --> 00:32:10.760
So "The Worthy"
was my third film.

00:32:10.760 --> 00:32:15.296
And there was many reasons
I wanted to do "The Worthy."

00:32:15.296 --> 00:32:16.670
One of the biggest
ones is that I

00:32:16.670 --> 00:32:19.640
didn't have to wait four years.

00:32:19.640 --> 00:32:21.530
I was in post-production
for "A to B,"

00:32:21.530 --> 00:32:25.790
and Image Nation Abu Dhabi,
they funded half of that movie.

00:32:25.790 --> 00:32:29.780
And they had this script
concept called "The Worthy."

00:32:29.780 --> 00:32:33.680
And they had two amazing
producers attached to it--

00:32:33.680 --> 00:32:38.990
Peter Safran, who produced
"The Conjuring" and "Annabelle"

00:32:38.990 --> 00:32:42.740
and those horror films,
and Stephen Schneider, who

00:32:42.740 --> 00:32:45.650
did "Insidious" and
"Paranormal Activity."

00:32:45.650 --> 00:32:49.940
So these guys made these
blockbuster Hollywood horror

00:32:49.940 --> 00:32:51.170
films.

00:32:51.170 --> 00:32:54.260
And they had this genre film
idea called "The Worthy."

00:32:54.260 --> 00:32:57.380
And it was set in a dystopian
post-apocalyptic world

00:32:57.380 --> 00:32:59.570
and about survival and so forth.

00:32:59.570 --> 00:33:01.580
And I read the script.

00:33:01.580 --> 00:33:03.590
But what I was told is
that I have to take this,

00:33:03.590 --> 00:33:09.530
and I have to make it our own,
Arabize it, and try and set it

00:33:09.530 --> 00:33:11.060
in the region.

00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:14.210
And so like I said, I didn't
have to wait four years.

00:33:14.210 --> 00:33:17.300
But also, it was a
genre that I would never

00:33:17.300 --> 00:33:19.520
have even thought of doing.

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:22.145
I don't know how many
of you are horror fans.

00:33:22.145 --> 00:33:23.450
SARA HAMDAN: No.

00:33:23.450 --> 00:33:26.240
ALI MOSTAFA: But I would
not go to the cinema

00:33:26.240 --> 00:33:28.550
to watch a horror film.

00:33:28.550 --> 00:33:30.980
Doesn't mean I don't
appreciate horror films

00:33:30.980 --> 00:33:35.270
or respect the
difficulty in making one.

00:33:35.270 --> 00:33:37.070
But it's just not
a thing I would do.

00:33:37.070 --> 00:33:39.260
It wouldn't be my first option.

00:33:39.260 --> 00:33:42.860
So the fact I've done
an ensemble drama,

00:33:42.860 --> 00:33:45.440
I've done a comedy,
this would be

00:33:45.440 --> 00:33:48.560
a challenge, something that
I would never think of doing.

00:33:48.560 --> 00:33:50.480
And I did it.

00:33:50.480 --> 00:33:52.580
And we shot it entirely
in Bucharest, Romania.

00:33:52.580 --> 00:33:55.250
So that was a great experience.

00:33:55.250 --> 00:34:00.320
And the film is now picked
up by Netflix worldwide.

00:34:00.320 --> 00:34:04.130
And so if you want to watch my
third film, it's on Netflix.

00:34:04.130 --> 00:34:07.130
SARA HAMDAN: Nice.

00:34:07.130 --> 00:34:08.566
Go ahead.

00:34:08.566 --> 00:34:10.316
AUDIENCE: So you say
the industry does not

00:34:10.316 --> 00:34:12.220
exist as such.

00:34:12.220 --> 00:34:14.255
It's not sustainable.

00:34:14.255 --> 00:34:15.130
ALI MOSTAFA: Not yet.

00:34:15.130 --> 00:34:18.495
AUDIENCE: Do
filmmakers make money?

00:34:18.495 --> 00:34:21.124
Did you break even
in your movies?

00:34:21.124 --> 00:34:23.889
ALI MOSTAFA: That's
a great question.

00:34:23.889 --> 00:34:26.170
Not one.

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:28.929
Not one of the films broke even.

00:34:28.929 --> 00:34:29.650
Not one.

00:34:29.650 --> 00:34:31.150
AUDIENCE: Even "City of Life"?

00:34:31.150 --> 00:34:32.139
ALI MOSTAFA: Even
"City of Life."

00:34:32.139 --> 00:34:33.469
"City of Life" did really well.

00:34:33.469 --> 00:34:36.280
But "City of Life" was
a $5 million movie.

00:34:36.280 --> 00:34:39.750
You can't make $5
million in ticket sales

00:34:39.750 --> 00:34:41.250
in Dubai those days.

00:34:41.250 --> 00:34:42.370
It was impossible.

00:34:42.370 --> 00:34:46.449
Now one of the
top big box office

00:34:46.449 --> 00:34:48.620
hits, the summer
box office hits,

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:53.050
in Dubai could go
up to $2 million,

00:34:53.050 --> 00:34:55.380
now, with the amount of cinemas.

00:34:55.380 --> 00:34:58.480
So that film needed
to have gone globally.

00:34:58.480 --> 00:35:00.610
Although we did sell
in different markets,

00:35:00.610 --> 00:35:03.520
still, it's a very
difficult industry

00:35:03.520 --> 00:35:05.680
to try and make money with.

00:35:05.680 --> 00:35:09.460
That's why you have to start
making films, which is a film

00:35:09.460 --> 00:35:11.490
that I would
probably like to do,

00:35:11.490 --> 00:35:14.680
that are very low budget
now because you know

00:35:14.680 --> 00:35:15.980
you can start breaking even.

00:35:15.980 --> 00:35:18.460
So once those films
start happening,

00:35:18.460 --> 00:35:20.620
they start to then
become sustainable.

00:35:20.620 --> 00:35:22.870
Then you can start
funding your next film.

00:35:22.870 --> 00:35:27.530
But unfortunately, my dream
was too big, too early.

00:35:27.530 --> 00:35:29.284
So I was making
big-budget movies.

00:35:29.284 --> 00:35:31.180
AUDIENCE: So people
actually fund

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:33.230
them knowing that they're
going to lose money?

00:35:33.230 --> 00:35:35.230
ALI MOSTAFA: Well, "City
of Life" was the first,

00:35:35.230 --> 00:35:36.063
so they had no idea.

00:35:36.063 --> 00:35:37.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:38.900 --> 00:35:42.010
The second one was-- both
were semi-government, who were

00:35:42.010 --> 00:35:45.130
trying to start an industry.

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:49.000
And the last one was fully
funded by Image Nation.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:53.950
And that's their mandate, is
to help create a film industry.

00:35:53.950 --> 00:35:56.719
AUDIENCE: Does it come with
strict strings attached?

00:35:56.719 --> 00:35:57.760
ALI MOSTAFA: In what way?

00:35:57.760 --> 00:36:00.394
AUDIENCE: Creatively.

00:36:00.394 --> 00:36:01.560
ALI MOSTAFA: Well, luckily--

00:36:01.560 --> 00:36:03.270
usually yes.

00:36:03.270 --> 00:36:08.580
Because when I did my
second film, I wrote.

00:36:08.580 --> 00:36:10.110
My first film, I wrote.

00:36:10.110 --> 00:36:12.700
So I wrote, produced, and
directed the first two films.

00:36:12.700 --> 00:36:16.020
This one, I was only
hired as a director.

00:36:16.020 --> 00:36:17.280
So usually, yes.

00:36:17.280 --> 00:36:19.950
Usually when you're with the
kind of the studio system,

00:36:19.950 --> 00:36:25.350
where you're hired as a hired
gun, in the creative side,

00:36:25.350 --> 00:36:28.290
you don't necessarily get
final cut of your edits

00:36:28.290 --> 00:36:29.375
or how you want it to be.

00:36:29.375 --> 00:36:31.500
But what was amazing with,
obviously, Image Nation,

00:36:31.500 --> 00:36:35.640
is that not only
are they producers

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:37.770
that are driven to
create this industry,

00:36:37.770 --> 00:36:39.780
but they're also
very creative people.

00:36:39.780 --> 00:36:42.000
And they support you.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:45.700
So yes, there was a
lot of discussions.

00:36:45.700 --> 00:36:49.420
But all the discussions were
very positive because we all--

00:36:49.420 --> 00:36:52.290
I think I'm now
on my third film.

00:36:52.290 --> 00:36:54.820
You kind of get what
you're trying to do.

00:36:54.820 --> 00:36:56.575
And everyone understands
we're doing this

00:36:56.575 --> 00:36:58.200
for the bigger picture
and for everyone

00:36:58.200 --> 00:37:01.020
to kind of be happy
with the end result.

00:37:01.020 --> 00:37:06.300
So not necessarily now, but
probably it will happen.

00:37:06.300 --> 00:37:07.290
But usually, yes.

00:37:07.290 --> 00:37:08.850
You do get a lot of constraints.

00:37:08.850 --> 00:37:11.266
Like, if I were probably gonna
do a film in Hollywood now,

00:37:11.266 --> 00:37:12.075
yeah.

00:37:12.075 --> 00:37:13.620
I'd be under reigns for sure.

00:37:17.786 --> 00:37:19.160
AUDIENCE: So I'd
like to also get

00:37:19.160 --> 00:37:22.322
your thoughts on the
[INAUDIBLE] movie

00:37:22.322 --> 00:37:24.322
and just overall, what
do you think is happening

00:37:24.322 --> 00:37:25.769
across the Arab world?

00:37:25.769 --> 00:37:27.310
Are there directors
you enjoy seeing?

00:37:27.310 --> 00:37:30.547
And I'd also like to see, are
there collaborations happening

00:37:30.547 --> 00:37:32.657
in Mideast in terms of
how the industry works?

00:37:32.657 --> 00:37:34.282
Is there a governing
body or something?

00:37:34.282 --> 00:37:36.280
Or there's really
nothing [INAUDIBLE]??

00:37:36.280 --> 00:37:39.400
ALI MOSTAFA: No,
we don't really--

00:37:39.400 --> 00:37:42.310
OK, the Egyptian cinema
obviously is a huge industry.

00:37:42.310 --> 00:37:43.350
Huge industry.

00:37:43.350 --> 00:37:48.070
They're their own beast,
their own machine.

00:37:48.070 --> 00:37:49.810
But there was a period--

00:37:49.810 --> 00:37:51.670
there was the golden
era, and then there

00:37:51.670 --> 00:37:53.920
was a period where they
were just producing--

00:37:53.920 --> 00:37:56.380
where even Egyptians would
say they were nonsense.

00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:59.140
And now they've come back
to start to produce and make

00:37:59.140 --> 00:38:01.874
some amazing films again.

00:38:01.874 --> 00:38:03.790
I was actually there
recently as a jury member

00:38:03.790 --> 00:38:07.527
for the first Gouna
Film Festival in Egypt.

00:38:07.527 --> 00:38:08.860
And I saw some incredible films.

00:38:08.860 --> 00:38:10.276
I actually saw
"The Insult," which

00:38:10.276 --> 00:38:12.980
is now nominated for Best
Foreign film at the Oscars,

00:38:12.980 --> 00:38:15.310
which is a Lebanese movie.

00:38:15.310 --> 00:38:17.020
And I really liked
that filmmaker.

00:38:17.020 --> 00:38:19.550
I liked his previous
work, as well.

00:38:19.550 --> 00:38:20.620
Ziad.

00:38:20.620 --> 00:38:24.280
And so is there a
real collaboration?

00:38:27.240 --> 00:38:28.390
There's trying to be one.

00:38:28.390 --> 00:38:30.940
I mean, there's this
Arab Film institute

00:38:30.940 --> 00:38:33.850
that's been created so we can
kind of break those borders

00:38:33.850 --> 00:38:35.560
and kind of work together.

00:38:35.560 --> 00:38:36.940
But I think there's
a bit of time

00:38:36.940 --> 00:38:40.300
with that because I made a
film, "From A to B," which

00:38:40.300 --> 00:38:45.670
was a Saudi, Syrian,
and an Egyptian,

00:38:45.670 --> 00:38:50.660
high-school friends go on a road
trip throughout the Arab world.

00:38:50.660 --> 00:38:55.360
So it was a very
pan-Arab movie, right?

00:38:55.360 --> 00:38:58.780
And it could have been
the time it was released

00:38:58.780 --> 00:39:00.295
or the marketing,
whatever may be.

00:39:00.295 --> 00:39:02.711
But it was a film you would
have thought, because it being

00:39:02.711 --> 00:39:05.740
so pan-Arab, that it would do
very well with Arab audiences,

00:39:05.740 --> 00:39:08.890
like in Egypt or in Jordan
or whatever it may be.

00:39:08.890 --> 00:39:09.970
And it didn't.

00:39:09.970 --> 00:39:13.630
So it was almost
like you almost felt

00:39:13.630 --> 00:39:19.906
that when the Egyptian films
come out here in Dubai, yes,

00:39:19.906 --> 00:39:21.280
they get a lot of
Arabs involved.

00:39:21.280 --> 00:39:23.890
But a lot of the Egyptians
go to see their films.

00:39:23.890 --> 00:39:25.750
A lot of Emiratis will
go see their films.

00:39:25.750 --> 00:39:28.750
And a lot of Lebanese
will see their films.

00:39:28.750 --> 00:39:31.650
Those films don't necessarily
kind of cross borders

00:39:31.650 --> 00:39:34.040
so well, which is a
shame because there

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:36.981
are some Lebanese
films, I believe,

00:39:36.981 --> 00:39:38.230
could do really well in Egypt.

00:39:38.230 --> 00:39:41.470
Or an Egyptian
film, I mean, they

00:39:41.470 --> 00:39:47.750
do really well regardless
given their [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:47.750 --> 00:39:49.510
massive population.

00:39:49.510 --> 00:39:52.490
But now that we
have Saudi Arabia,

00:39:52.490 --> 00:39:55.165
that it decided
to open theaters,

00:39:55.165 --> 00:39:56.790
this is one of the
things why it's also

00:39:56.790 --> 00:40:01.510
so positive because "City
of Life" released today,

00:40:01.510 --> 00:40:03.490
we would have made our
money back, you know?

00:40:03.490 --> 00:40:07.460
So the industry is growing.

00:40:07.460 --> 00:40:09.580
The fact there's now
Saudis opening cinemas,

00:40:09.580 --> 00:40:13.000
the fact there's this Arab
Film Institute is happening--

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:16.210
we have a Lebanese film
who's nominated for an Oscar

00:40:16.210 --> 00:40:17.580
this year.

00:40:17.580 --> 00:40:21.490
And I think it should win.

00:40:21.490 --> 00:40:22.990
I haven't seen the
other contenders.

00:40:22.990 --> 00:40:28.630
But since "Paradise
Now," we need one.

00:40:28.630 --> 00:40:30.630
And it's important.

00:40:30.630 --> 00:40:34.180
But I do think those
borders are gonna drop,

00:40:34.180 --> 00:40:38.830
and it is gonna become
a lot more accessible.

00:40:38.830 --> 00:40:41.224
Yeah, for sure.

00:40:41.224 --> 00:40:42.907
AUDIENCE: Do you
get your films to be

00:40:42.907 --> 00:40:48.540
screened in Emirates or Etihad
in-flight entertainment?

00:40:48.540 --> 00:40:49.790
ALI MOSTAFA: I was very lucky.

00:40:49.790 --> 00:40:53.342
Actually, my first
film, "City of Life"--

00:40:53.342 --> 00:40:55.740
actually, I should
not talk about that.

00:40:55.740 --> 00:40:59.410
But my first film,
"City of Life"

00:40:59.410 --> 00:41:04.190
was in Emirates, although
we had a flight attendant

00:41:04.190 --> 00:41:07.040
and we had an airline
in "City of Life."

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:09.540
But I had to make one up.

00:41:09.540 --> 00:41:12.770
But after the fact, Emirates
were very supportive

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:16.370
and saw that it was
something that was important.

00:41:16.370 --> 00:41:19.270
They put it as the
first film on in-flight.

00:41:19.270 --> 00:41:21.470
I think it was on the plane
for, like, two months.

00:41:21.470 --> 00:41:24.350
They put me on the cover
of "Open Skies" magazine.

00:41:24.350 --> 00:41:25.810
I was interviewed during--

00:41:25.810 --> 00:41:28.266
while people would see the
opening film of the safety,

00:41:28.266 --> 00:41:30.890
after that, there was me giving
an interview on "City of Life."

00:41:30.890 --> 00:41:32.770
So they were very supportive.

00:41:32.770 --> 00:41:37.260
"A to B," obviously, had some
Etihad exposure in the film.

00:41:37.260 --> 00:41:38.690
So it was played in Etihad.

00:41:38.690 --> 00:41:41.030
Actually, it was also
played in Emirates.

00:41:41.030 --> 00:41:45.030
But there were certain
scenes that were removed.

00:41:45.030 --> 00:41:48.800
And yeah, so the airlines
are very supportive.

00:41:48.800 --> 00:41:53.930
We're very lucky to have
the airlines, the press.

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:54.830
They're excited.

00:41:54.830 --> 00:41:58.550
I mean, I think everyone's as
hungry to have a film industry,

00:41:58.550 --> 00:42:00.490
also.

00:42:00.490 --> 00:42:03.430
SARA HAMDAN: You had
a question back there.

00:42:03.430 --> 00:42:05.737
AUDIENCE: What was the reaction
from the general public

00:42:05.737 --> 00:42:09.489
in Dubai-- can you break it
down in terms of expats versus

00:42:09.489 --> 00:42:11.365
locals--

00:42:11.365 --> 00:42:15.200
to some of the controversial
subjects in the movie?

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:20.050
Has it stimulated the debate
about Dubai's identity

00:42:20.050 --> 00:42:21.020
[INAUDIBLE].

00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:27.864
ALI MOSTAFA: You see,
I guess the movie that

00:42:27.864 --> 00:42:29.280
comes to mind,
obviously, would be

00:42:29.280 --> 00:42:30.530
"City of Life" for me in that.

00:42:30.530 --> 00:42:33.497
Because when that film was
released in the theaters,

00:42:33.497 --> 00:42:35.580
and I was going to the
cinema to watch, let's say,

00:42:35.580 --> 00:42:38.040
another movie, I would
pass by the hall.

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:41.070
And I would hear
my film playing.

00:42:41.070 --> 00:42:43.072
And I would tell the
usher, just one second.

00:42:43.072 --> 00:42:45.030
I just want to take a
quick look from the back.

00:42:45.030 --> 00:42:46.870
And I would just step
in every now and then

00:42:46.870 --> 00:42:51.750
in the theaters to see reaction,
but also to see the audience.

00:42:51.750 --> 00:42:58.140
And it was such a huge mix
of different nationalities.

00:42:58.140 --> 00:43:01.530
There was the Indian community.

00:43:01.530 --> 00:43:03.420
You had the Western
community, the Emiratis,

00:43:03.420 --> 00:43:05.830
and all of them sitting
there watching this one film.

00:43:08.930 --> 00:43:13.820
What I found unfortunate
is that that is slowly--

00:43:13.820 --> 00:43:18.500
because it was such a film that
spoke to so many nationalities,

00:43:18.500 --> 00:43:21.830
that I feel it's unfortunate
that we have not now

00:43:21.830 --> 00:43:26.120
made Emirati films of
a standard, as yet--

00:43:26.120 --> 00:43:29.060
when I see Emirati,
like, pure Emirati--

00:43:29.060 --> 00:43:32.120
that can bring in an
international audience

00:43:32.120 --> 00:43:33.350
to watch it, too.

00:43:33.350 --> 00:43:35.240
I think once we reach
that stage where

00:43:35.240 --> 00:43:41.720
we make a fully Arabic-spoken,
Arabic-produced, cast Emirati

00:43:41.720 --> 00:43:45.080
film and still have a
similar audience, that

00:43:45.080 --> 00:43:46.970
will go to show that
we've reached a level

00:43:46.970 --> 00:43:51.440
where we're now
speaking to Dubai.

00:43:51.440 --> 00:43:52.250
And what is Dubai?

00:43:52.250 --> 00:43:56.180
Dubai is such a
multicultural place.

00:43:56.180 --> 00:44:00.715
So I think you need a
bit more time with that.

00:44:00.715 --> 00:44:02.840
SARA HAMDAN: You can test
it out by doing a YouTube

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:07.210
show, a series, episodes.

00:44:07.210 --> 00:44:08.610
Just putting that out there.

00:44:08.610 --> 00:44:10.776
ALI MOSTAFA: I would love
to do a series on YouTube,

00:44:10.776 --> 00:44:13.130
but not one of those
kind of blogger, selfie,

00:44:13.130 --> 00:44:14.180
influencer ones now.

00:44:14.180 --> 00:44:16.230
That's not something I can do.

00:44:16.230 --> 00:44:17.480
I'm not good at that.

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:17.768
SARA HAMDAN: I'm a blogger.

00:44:17.768 --> 00:44:19.601
AUDIENCE: I have a
question related to the--

00:44:19.601 --> 00:44:21.735
ALI MOSTAFA: Well, but
you're a good blogger.

00:44:21.735 --> 00:44:22.860
I'll be a terrible blogger.

00:44:22.860 --> 00:44:24.109
SARA HAMDAN: I'm just kidding.

00:44:24.109 --> 00:44:24.866
Go ahead.

00:44:24.866 --> 00:44:27.830
AUDIENCE: I have a
question related to when

00:44:27.830 --> 00:44:29.331
you work with advertisers.

00:44:29.331 --> 00:44:30.080
ALI MOSTAFA: Yeah.

00:44:30.080 --> 00:44:32.430
AUDIENCE: You said that
it's very difficult

00:44:32.430 --> 00:44:35.305
to do something different.

00:44:35.305 --> 00:44:37.430
ALI MOSTAFA: I don't blame
the advertising, though.

00:44:37.430 --> 00:44:38.165
I blame the clients.

00:44:38.165 --> 00:44:38.915
AUDIENCE: Exactly.

00:44:38.915 --> 00:44:45.394
But I want to understand
what other kind of friction

00:44:45.394 --> 00:44:50.204
you have with them in trying
to pitch new ideas or new kind

00:44:50.204 --> 00:44:50.940
of--

00:44:50.940 --> 00:44:53.523
ALI MOSTAFA: You know, I've also
been very lucky where clients

00:44:53.523 --> 00:44:55.292
sometimes approach me directly.

00:44:55.292 --> 00:44:56.750
And they approach
me, and they say,

00:44:56.750 --> 00:45:00.140
listen, we have this product, or
we have this-- whatever it be,

00:45:00.140 --> 00:45:02.660
this car, this resort.

00:45:02.660 --> 00:45:06.202
Would you be able to
make an ad or film on it?

00:45:06.202 --> 00:45:08.660
That's when we can go back,
and we can start creating ideas

00:45:08.660 --> 00:45:09.710
ourselves.

00:45:09.710 --> 00:45:11.866
And you skip the
whole middleman.

00:45:11.866 --> 00:45:13.490
And because they
approach you directly,

00:45:13.490 --> 00:45:15.910
they kind of listen
to what's going on.

00:45:15.910 --> 00:45:22.070
But when you have the
client, the agency, and then

00:45:22.070 --> 00:45:26.630
the production, unfortunately,
a lot of the times,

00:45:26.630 --> 00:45:30.290
you end up giving up the
fight because you realize,

00:45:30.290 --> 00:45:32.390
is it really worth it?

00:45:32.390 --> 00:45:35.540
But sometimes you really like
the commercial or the content

00:45:35.540 --> 00:45:38.310
or the copy, and you really try
and fight it to make it better.

00:45:38.310 --> 00:45:42.290
But unfortunately, I feel it's
the client that needs to be

00:45:42.290 --> 00:45:48.710
more educated on what they can
or cannot show or understand

00:45:48.710 --> 00:45:50.150
film.

00:45:50.150 --> 00:45:51.530
Because there's
a lot of the time

00:45:51.530 --> 00:45:54.410
you would have this person who
might be the head of marketing

00:45:54.410 --> 00:45:59.060
for whatever company
who has no idea

00:45:59.060 --> 00:46:02.312
or has no background about what
is a good commercial, what's

00:46:02.312 --> 00:46:03.020
a bad commercial.

00:46:03.020 --> 00:46:06.530
It's pure feeling on the day.

00:46:06.530 --> 00:46:12.350
I had an instance where I
was shooting a certain car

00:46:12.350 --> 00:46:16.160
commercial many years ago, where
the head marketing of that car

00:46:16.160 --> 00:46:19.355
brand decided, after I
edited the director's cut,

00:46:19.355 --> 00:46:22.830
came in the next day, edited
the whole film himself,

00:46:22.830 --> 00:46:24.380
and then released it.

00:46:24.380 --> 00:46:27.980
And I said, you have to
remove my name from that.

00:46:27.980 --> 00:46:30.350
Because it's not
what I had done.

00:46:30.350 --> 00:46:32.650
So there's a lot of the
times where-- obviously, it

00:46:32.650 --> 00:46:34.670
